>btw for any artists itt what program do you use to make digital art? i tried using paint dot net but obviously the options there are pretty limited
I have way too many opinions on this subject. I go to art school, so I've argued way too many times about which programs are best.
My personal most used programs are Procreate on the iPad and Paint Tool Sai on the PC. However, I wouldn't reccomend Paint Tool Sai to everyone. I like it because it has insanely good blending that literally no other art program has managed to replicate, even though it's an old and very simple program. If you don't want to do paintings I wouldn't reccomend it and even if you do it's probably best for you to learn and get used to a more complete program than it anyway, even if they have inferior blending.
Clip Studio Paint is by far the most complete art program we have, in my opinion. I haven't used it very often because I hate having to learn a new program when I just want to draw, but if you're looking for a program to learn this is the one I'd reccomend. It even has pretty good animation features, if you're into that.
Photoshop is not an art program and never will be. I've argued about this multiple times. The brush engine is absolute shit. The blending is horrible. It is the most complete option in terms of photo manipulation and all that so I can see why some people use it, but I still don't like it as an art program.
Krita is free, and that's pretty much what it has going for it. It's leagues better than Paint.NET, and the animation feature in it is pretty usable, too. I like the blending here better than Photoshop blending but even Clip is better, IMO.
People who use Corel Painter are insane, but I haven't used it enough to talk about it myself. I don't like Adobe Fresco, but I am biased against Adobe and have not tested it too much myself, either. Illustrator is a vector program so I don't even place it in the same category as other art programs.

Lunch Edition

Goal of the thread: Treat yourself to something nice, be it a meal, a hot bath, or something else you'd enjoy doing.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

Deep stealth (as opposed to semi-stealth) means you typically cut off anyone who already knows you are trans, such as family and old friends. Sometimes this requires moving away. You don't tell your new coworkers and new friends that you are trans, and lie when necessary to keep them thinking you are cis. Although usually even for deep stealth it becomes necessary to come out as trans to your romantic partner, some deep stealth people thus choose never to date.

It is considered a more extreme solution but it does mean that basically no one knows you are trans and so there is very low chance of you being outed and you are completely treated as cis. Some people only go deep stealth after they have secured a romantic partner who knows they are trans, and they trust that partner to keep that fact to themselves.

Most trans people seem to do semi-stealth instead, which is to go to work but barely socialise there and be presumed cis. Then keep a separate social life where their friends are pre-filtered to be trans-accepting (sometimes this means sticking to other trans people) and being openly trans there. They also usually come out to family members and old friends who matter to them, to give those a chance to accept them as trans, then decide based on reaction whether to keep those people in their lives.

But some deep stealth people do not do semi-stealth, as they fear that anyone at all knowing they are trans, might react badly in ways that result in social fallout, or may accidentally leak the fact to others.

As for "what personality is good for deep stealth", a person suited for deep stealth is someone who doesn't see their birth sex or being trans as anything significant at all (as opposed to a core part of their identity), doesn't mind telling small lies, doesn't feel lonely as a result of telling said small lies, isn't too focused on personal authenticity and honesty, and has poor/loose/no social ties to their pre-trans lives.

The biggest difference I have seen between Thailand and Korea is culture-mediated attitudes of politeness. Korea has a more gruff kind of "fuck you this is what I think" brutal honesty relative to other asian cultures, so the culture is more openly transphobic compared to Thailand even when legal recognitions are better.

Thailand is very Buddhist, and Buddhism is all about tolerance and courtesy. I live in Singapore which is also a type of conservative where open transphobia is already very rare and most people are polite introverts, but even then, plenty of other Singaporean trans people I know talk about how Thailand is even better in terms of socially treating trans people well and being nice to them and having some baseline understanding of what it means to be trans. Beneath it all of course, plenty of Thai people still see birth sex as very important to their conception of trans people, so that combination of underlying conservatism with their good social treatment of trans people can be hard to detail.
